(a) A symmetric difference B
The symmetric difference of two sets A and B is the set of elements that are in either A or B, but not in both. In other words, it is the union of the sets minus their intersection.

A symmetric difference B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B)

A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7}
A ∩ B = {5}

A symmetric difference B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7}

(b) B symmetric difference A
The symmetric difference is commutative, which means that A symmetric difference B is equal to B symmetric difference A.

B symmetric difference A = (B ∪ A) - (B ∩ A)

B ∪ A = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7}
B ∩ A = {5}

B symmetric difference A = {1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7}

As we can see, the answer to parts (a) and (b) are the same, which shows that the symmetric difference is commutative.

(c) A intersection (A symmetric difference B)
A intersection (A symmetric difference B) = A ∩ {1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7}

A intersection (A symmetric difference B) = {1, 3, 7}

(d) (A intersection B) symmetric difference B
(A intersection B) symmetric difference B = {5} symmetric difference {2, 4, 5, 6}

(A intersection B) symmetric difference B = {2, 4, 6}

The original statement asked to show that the answer to parts (a) and (b) are not the same, which would prove that the symmetric difference of two sets is not commutative with respect to intersection. However, as we have shown, the symmetric difference is commutative, and the answers to parts (a) and (b) are the same.
